{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17499733","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17499733"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-29T10:01:49+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-29T10:01:49+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"1526"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"1526","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/1526"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.36,0.2,0.08,0.23,0.13]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"1526"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"79835"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"1526","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/1526"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"1526"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"65131"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"8"},{"type":"tags","id":"24"},{"type":"tags","id":"64"},{"type":"tags","id":"72"},{"type":"tags","id":"76"},{"type":"tags","id":"804"},{"type":"tags","id":"1193"},{"type":"tags","id":"1207"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"2286"},{"type":"contributions","id":"2958"},{"type":"contributions","id":"27260"},{"type":"contributions","id":"27291"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"79835","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/79835"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA 25-year-old man presents to the Emergency Department with severe eye pain whilst welding without eye shields. He has no significant medical history and takes no regular medications. He has never had eye surgery.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EOn examination, he appears distressed. His pulse rate is 90/min, blood pressure 130/80 mmHg, respiratory rate 18/min, SpO2 98% on room air, and temperature 36.8\u00b0C. Visual acuity cannot be assessed due to pain. Close inspection of the cornea is undertaken (Image).\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following is the most appropriate next step in management?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Eye shield","Copious irrigation","Topical atropine drops","Removal with 16mm hypodermic needle","B-scan ultrasonography"],"correctOptions":[0],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThis patient presents with iris prolapse through a corneal perforation following ocular trauma. This is a sight-threatening emergency requiring immediate specialist intervention. The dark tissue protruding through the cornea represents prolapsed iris tissue, indicating globe rupture.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EEye shield \u003C/strong\u003Eand urgent ophthalmological referral\u003Cstrong\u003E \u003C/strong\u003Eis essential to prevent further tissue prolapse and reduce the risk of infection. An eye shield provides protection without putting pressure on the globe. The patient should be positioned upright during transport to minimise further prolapse.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ECopious irrigation\u003C/strong\u003E would be inappropriate and potentially harmful in this case as it risks further tissue prolapse and contamination of the open globe. Irrigation is useful for chemical burns or foreign body removal but contraindicated in globe perforation.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ETopical atropine drops\u003C/strong\u003E, while useful for cycloplegia in some eye conditions, is inappropriate as first-line management for globe perforation. Any manipulation of the eye risks worsening the injury.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ERemoval with 16mm hypodermic needle\u003C/strong\u003E would be extremely dangerous and could cause catastrophic damage to the eye. Any attempted manipulation of prolapsed iris tissue should only be performed by an ophthalmologist in a controlled surgical setting.  If the iris was not involved and there was a superficial foreign body with good visualisation then it may be appropriate to remove with a hypodermic needle in an experienced clinician. \u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EB-scan ultrasonography\u003C/strong\u003E is contraindicated in suspected globe perforation as the pressure from the ultrasound probe could worsen the injury and cause further tissue prolapse.  This would be a better investigation if there was a closed globe injury and assessment needs to be made for an absent lens.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe management priorities are protecting the eye from further damage with an eye shield, preventing infection, and arranging immediate ophthalmological assessment for surgical repair. The patient should receive appropriate analgesia and anti-emetics, and should remain nil by mouth in preparation for likely surgery.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["Traumatic iris prolapse requires immediate eye shield application and urgent ophthalmological referral to prevent further damage.","Globe perforation requires careful handling to prevent worsening of tissue prolapse.","Endophthalmitis is a sight-threatening complication of globe perforation requiring immediate intervention."],"references":["Bowling B. Kanski\u2019s clinical ophthalmology (8th ed.). W B Saunders. .2015.","Heath Jeffery R, Dobes J, Chen F. Eye injuries: Understanding ocular trauma. Australian Journal for General Practitioners. 2022;51:476-82. Available at: https://www1.racgp.org.au/ajgp/2022/july/eye-injuries"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"65131"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"1526"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[{"type":"media","id":"18413"}]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"media","id":"18413","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/media/18413"},"attribute